Citations
Date: 9/11/1852
Source: NZ Government Gazette
Author:
Vol / Page: V/26/165
Edition:
Quote: ...a hole was dug ... and a quantity of the soil washed, but without any visible satisfactory result ... [A] favourable indication was noticed at a bar in the creek, and a quantity of the gravel and earth removed, a panful was taken from about two feet below the surface and washed, it produced a number of scales of gold.
Notes: (Report of Sub-Committee on Recent Gold Discovery in the Coromandel District)

Date: 0/0/1853
Source: New Zealand (various authors/titles)
Author: EARP
Vol / Page: 255
Edition:
Quote: I went there [to Arataonga] yesterday `prospecting', and found gold in the first pan washed.
Notes: 1852 Nov 10 (Auckland) in 1853 Earp NZ 255

Date: 0/0/1974
Source: Bright Fine Gold
Author: HEINZ
Vol / Page: 108
Edition:
Quote: Your committee had a quantity of stuff taken out of this hole and washed under their inspection, and every panful produced a few specks of gold.
Notes: 1853 Earp NZ in 1974 Heinz Bright Fine Gold 108

Date: 29/6/1861
Source: Otago Witness
Author:
Vol / Page: 5
Edition:
Quote: The only tools we took with us were, a spade, tin dish, and pannikin. We tried a number of places along the bed of the creek, sinking in each from two to four feet; out of the whole we washed not more than six buckets full, ...
Notes:

Date: 0/0/1960
Source: Over the Whitcombe Pass
Author: PASCOE
Vol / Page: 42
Edition:
Quote: ... looking towards the bank of the stream I observed some splendid looking washing stuff - fine gravel mixed with quartz and ironstone. I took the lid of the billy and washed about two handsful, and found some fine specks of gold - what diggers call `the colour'.
Notes: 1863 Lauper in 1960 Pascoe (ed) Over the Whitcombe Pass 42

